SIMPLE: hull
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hull
<hw>Hull</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hul</ets>,
<ets>hol</ets>, shell, husk, AS. <ets>hulu</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>h⟦uum⟧lle</ets> covering, husk, case, <ets>h⟦uum⟧llen</ets> to
cover, Goth. <ets>huljan</ets> to cover, AS. <ets>helan</ets> to hele,
conceal. ⟦root⟧17. See <er>Hele</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>,
<er>Hell</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The outer covering of anything,
particularly of a nut or of grain; the outer skin of a kernel; the
husk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[In this sense perh. influenced by D. <ets>hol</ets>
hold of a ship, E. <ets>hold</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The
frame or body of a vessel, exclusive of her masts, yards, sails, and
rigging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Deep in their <qex>hulls</qex> our deadly bullets light.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hull down</b></col>, <cd>said of a ship so distant that
her hull is concealed by the convexity of the sea.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hull
<hw>Hull</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hulled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hulling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strip off or
separate the hull or hulls of; to free from integument; <as>as, to
<ex>hull</ex> corn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pierce the hull of, as a ship, with a cannon
ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hull
<hw>Hull</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To toss or drive on the water, like
the hull of a ship without sails.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak. Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hullabaloo</ent>⟦br⟧
